author = {Yasushi Takai},
abstract = {Isolation of oogonial stem cells and their application In 2004, Johnson et al. reported findings suggesting oocyte regeneration in the adult mouse ovary, and several research groups from around the world have reported the possibility that oogonial stem cells (OSCs) exist in the ovary after birth. In 2012, White et al. isolated OSCs from human frozen ovarian tissue. When GFP-labeled human OSCs were injected into human ovarian tissue fragments and these tissue fragments were xenotransplanted into mice, primordial follicles with flat cells surrounding GFP-positive cells were observed. For ethical and legal reasons, oocytes derived from human OSCs could not be fertilized with human sperm, but when GFP-labeled mouse OSCs were injected into the ovaries of infertile mice, pups expressing GFP were obtained. In the future, it may be possible to safely obtain many mature oocytes by isolating OSCs from frozen ovarian tissue, growing them in an in vitro culture system that does not contain cancer cells, inducing differentiation in an artificial ovary in vitro, and reimplanting them in the remaining gonadal tissue. On the other hand, germline stem cells and granulosa cells derived from ES and iPS cells, as well as OSCs derived from ovarian tissue, are expected to be applied to reproductive medicine. Isolation of endometrial stem cells and their application To date, four kinds of endometrial stem cells (eSC) are identified in the endometrium; epithelial stem cells, mesenchymal stem cells (eMSC), side population stem cells, and very small embryonic-like stem cells. Although the specific role of eSCs has not been investigated so far, intrauterine transplantation of eMSCs derived from menstrual blood flow has been reported to increase endometrial thickness in humans. Future studies on the functional mechanisms of eMSCs in the development of endometrial disorders would be beneficial for the treatment of damaged endometrium.}
}
